{
  "answer": "**In the *Manusmṛti* (Laws of Manu), Chapter 10 prescribes rigid, divinely ordained duties (*svadharma*) for each *varṇa*, derived from the primordial body of the Creator and enforced by cosmic consequences like caste degradation or rebirth penalties.**[^1][^2] A representative norm is the Shudra's sole proper occupation: service to Brahmins, as \"whatever else he does besides this becomes fruitless for him.\"[^3]\n\n**By contrast, *Maxims I* (in *Old English Elegies*) offers gnomic wisdom on social roles in proverbial terms like \"sceal\" (\"shall/must\") or \"geriseð\" (\"is fitting\"), blending observation of customary norms with implicit ideals, without explicit sanctions.**[^4] A representative norm matching the *varṇa*-like structure: \"A warrior must be on his horse's back, the cavalry must ride in a troop, the foot-soldiers stand fast. A maiden is fitting at her embroidery.\"[^5]\n\n**On its own terms, the *Maxims* norm would be easier to argue out of.** Manu's prescriptions are absolute *Dharma*, tied to creation itself (e.g., Shudras from the feet), with no exceptions beyond dire distress—and even then, reversion is mandated.[^6] Violations entail eternal downfall. The *Maxims*, however, evoke a natural, worldly order (\"as many peoples as there are customs\"), open to Fate (*wyrd*), exception, or change; they praise virtue amid variability (e.g., \"Blessed is he who thrives... wretched is he whom his friends betray\") without cosmic enforcement, allowing counterexamples from \"grim seasons\" or personal thriving.[^7]\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 10, [translation](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 1, [translation](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-13a2db).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 10, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/#p-b2dc48).\n\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Maxims I\", [translation](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/).\n\n[^5]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Maxims I\", [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/#p-84cf09).\n\n[^6]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 10, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/#p-53206d).\n\n[^7]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Maxims I\", [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/#p-84cf09).",
